This section will explore the structure and composition of the Olympic dataset.

Dataset Description and Source¶

This dataset, titled "120 Years of Olympic History: Athletes and Results", provides comprehensive information on all athletes who have competed in the modern Olympic Games from Athens 1896 to Rio 2016. Each row in the dataset represents a single athlete’s participation in a specific event. The data contains both Summer and Winter Games data, which were held in the same year until 1992 and staggered thereafter.

Source: The data was scraped from sports-reference.com and made available on Kaggle.

Key Columns:

Name, Sex, Age, Height, Weight — Athlete demographics

Team, NOC — Country representation

Sport, Event — Event classification

Year, Season, City — Temporal and spatial context

Medal — Awarded medal (Gold, Silver, Bronze, or NA)

Filling Missing Values¶

In [51]:
#filling missing "Medal" values with "No Medal"
df["Medal"].fillna("No Medal", inplace = True)

Missing values for Age, Height, and Weight are filled with medians based on Sport and Sex. This approach preserves the physical differences between sports and genders.

No rows were dropped in order to avoid distorting other relevant columns.

Age¶

In [130]:
#create a dataframe with median per sport and sex
age_medians = df.groupby(["Sport", "Sex"])["Age"].median().reset_index()
age_medians.rename(columns = {"Age": "Median_Age"}, inplace = True)

#merge medians back into main dataframe
df = df.merge(age_medians, on = ["Sport","Sex"], how = "left")

#fill missing values with group median
df["Age"].fillna(df["Median_Age"], inplace = True)

#drop helper column
df.drop(columns = ["Median_Age"], inplace = True)

After performing group-based median imputation for Height and Weight, I checked which sports still contained missing values.

For Weight, missing values were associated with the following sports: Art Competitions, Polo, Cricket, Racquets, Military Ski Patrol, Croquet, Jeu De Paume, Roque, Alpinism, Basque Pelota, Motorboating, Aeronautics

For Height, the missing values were found in: Cricket, Military Ski Patrol, Croquet, Roque, Alpinism, Basque Pelota, Motorboating, Aeronautics

I filled the remaining missing Height and Weight values using the overall median for each column to preserve all rows while minimizing bias introduced by extreme values or outliers.

New Columns¶

In [146]:
#column to flag wether an athlete won a medal
df["Is Medalist"] = df["Medal"] != "No Medal"
df["Is Medalist"] = df["Is Medalist"].astype(int)

The Is_Medalist column was created to flag whether an athlete won any medal. The column was grouped with a boolean comparison to assign 1 to medalists and 0 otherwise.

In [147]:
#column to group decades
df["Decade"] = (df["Year"] // 10) * 10
In [148]:
#column to group by medal type
medal_map = {"Gold": 3, "Silver": 2, "Bronze": 1, "No Medal": 0}
df["Medal Value"] = df["Medal"].map(medal_map)

Summary of additional cleaning¶

  • The Country column was cleaned for capitalization and spacing.
  • New columns were derived to simplify downstream analysis:
  • Is Medalist: A binary flag indicating if the athlete received any medal.
  • Decade: Created from the Year column to support decadal trend analysis.
  • Medal Value: Converted medal types into numeric values (Gold = 3, Silver = 2, Bronze = 1, No Medal = 0).

Data Viz and interpretation¶

1. Medal Trends Over Time by Gender¶

In [155]:
# Medal trends over time by gender
medalists = df[df["Medal"] != "No Medal"]
gender_trend = medalists.groupby(["Year", "Sex"]).size().reset_index(name="Medal Count")

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
sns.lineplot(data=gender_trend, x="Year", y="Medal Count", hue="Sex", marker="o")
plt.title("Medal Trends Over Time by Gender")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Number of Medals")
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation¶

This line chart shows how medal counts have grown over time for both male and female athletes. You can immediately see a sharp increase in female medalists from the 1980s onward, reflecting global progress in gender inclusion in sports.

Heatmap of Medals by Sport and Year¶

In [156]:
# Filter data to include only medalists
medalists = df[df["Medal"] != "No Medal"]

# Group by Sport and Year to count medals
heatmap_data = medalists.groupby(["Sport", "Year"]).size().unstack(fill_value=0)

# Plot heatmap with larger axis labels and tick sizes
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, cmap="YlGnBu", linewidths=0.5)

plt.title("Heatmap of Medals by Sport and Year", fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Sport", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation¶

A heatmap of medal counts by sport and year highlights event concentration. Sports like Athletics, Swimming, and Gymnastics consistently appear across decades with high medal volumes. Others, such as Art Competitions, appear briefly and then disappear, reflecting changes in Olympic programming.

BMI Distribution by Sport (Top 10)¶

In [160]:
# BMI distribution by sport
df["BMI"] = df["Weight"] / ((df["Height"] / 100) ** 2)

# Only include valid rows with non-null BMI values
top_10_sports = df["Sport"].value_counts().head(10).index
bmi_data = df[df["Sport"].isin(top_10_sports) & df["BMI"].notnull()]

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=bmi_data, x="Sport", y="BMI")
plt.title("BMI Distribution by Sport (Top 10 Sports)")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation¶

A box plot of BMI distributions across the 10 most represented sports shows substantial variation. Although the IQRs are fairly similar in distribution, sports like Gymnastics and Fencing have lower average BMIs, while Weightlifting and Wrestling show higher averages with wider distributions. These insights emphasize the physical demands unique to each sport.

#importing plotly for advanced visualizations
import plotly.express as px

# interactive line chart for average athlete age over time
age_trend = df[df["Age"].notnull()].groupby("Year")["Age"].mean().reset_index()

# Interactive line chart for average age
fig1 = px.line(
    age_trend,
    x="Year", y="Age",
    title="Average Athlete Age Over Time",
    markers=True,
    labels={"Age": "Average Age"}
)
fig1.write_html("avgage_time.html")
fig1.show()

Interpretation:¶

The average age of Olympic athletes has remained relatively stable, fluctuating between 23 and 26 over the decades. Minor dips and spikes may reflect changes in sport composition, generational athletic peaks, or inclusion of more youth-focused events in recent Games

    title="Medal Count by Gender Across Decades",
    labels={"Medal Count": "Number of Medals"}
)

# Show the plot
fig.write_html("medal_trend_decade.html")
fig.show()

Interpretation¶

Visualizes the rise in female medal counts across time, especially from the 1980s onward.

Conclusioin¶

Key Findings¶

  • There is a strong correlation between country participation size and medal outcomes
  • Summer Games dominate both participation and awards
  • Gender equity is growing, notably since the 1980s
  • Height and age distributions of medalists revealed distinct patterns by gender and event type, while BMI comparisons emphasized sport-specific bias
  • Disparities in medal counts across global regions and emphasized how the structure of Olympic competition privileges certain nations and events over others.
